{"key":"post-16941468","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16941468</id>\n<content>Mycelium rips through coir because it's an excellent bulk substrate material.&amp;nbsp; Coir has few nutes plants use thus it makes a great hydroponic medium.&amp;nbsp; However, mycelium breaks down solids at the cellular level, and coir has lots of cell structure for mycelium to feed on.&amp;nbsp; I've spawned bulk to coir/verm and plain coir and performance is similar to horse manure or straw.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Coir also performs well after sterilizing because the heat cooks it, making it easier for the mycelium to digest.&amp;nbsp; Sterilizing bulk substrates such as manure can lead to a higher incidence of contaminants, but not so with coir.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16941487</next>\n<prev>16940520</prev>\n<first>16938037</first>\n<last>16941593</last>\n<when>1349061954</when>\n<utime>10/01/12 06:25 AM</utime>\n</post>"}